  "prompt": "Is money laundering illegal?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is illegal in virtually every country around the world. It involves the process of making illegally obtained money (often referred to as \"dirty money\") appear to be legally earned (or \"clean\") by passing it through legitimate businesses, financial systems, or transactions. This is done to disguise the money's illicit origins and integrate it into the formal economy.\n\nMoney laundering is a serious crime because it enables criminal activities such as drug trafficking, terrorism, fraud, corruption, and organized crime to continue and expand. Laws and regulations against money laundering are enforced by financial institutions, law enforcement agencies, and international bodies like the Financial Action Task Force (FATF).\n\nPenalties for money laundering can be severe, including substantial fines, imprisonment, and the forfeiture of assets. Individuals, businesses, and financial institutions found complicit in money laundering can face legal consequences.",
